":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Battle of Homildon Hill Northumberland, England":"Battle, Berkshire, Anglie","Scotland":"Scotland"},"da":{"1366–14 September 1402":"1366–14. september 1402","1366–1402":"1366–1402","1360–1410":"1360–1410","1381–1420":"1381–1420","1342–1404":"1342–1404","1332–1381":"1332–1381","before 1366":"før 1366","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1404":"1404","1402":"1402","1366":"1366","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1378":"omkring 1378","about 1385":"omkring 1385","14 September 1402":"14. september 1402","Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Darnley, Renfrewshire, Skotland","Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Skotland","Battle of Homildon Hill Northumberland, England":"Battle, Berkshire, England","Scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"1366–14 September 1402":"1366–14 september 1402","1366–1402":"1366–1402","1360–1410":"1360–1410","1381–1420":"1381–1420","1342–1404":"1342–1404","1332–1381":"1332–1381","before 1366":"vóór 1366","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1404":"1404","1402":"1402","1366":"1366","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1378":"circa 1378","about 1385":"circa 1385","14 September 1402":"14 september 1402","Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Darnley, Renfrewshire, Schotland","Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Schotland","Battle of Homildon Hill Northumberland, England":"Battle, Berkshire, England","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1366–14 September 1402":"1366–14 September 1402","1366–1402":"1366–1402","1360–1410":"1360–1410","1381–1420":"1381–1420","1342–1404":"1342–1404","1332–1381":"1332–1381","before 1366":"before 1366","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1404":"1404","1402":"1402","1366":"1366","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1378":"about 1378","about 1385":"about 1385","14 September 1402":"14 September 1402","Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Battle of Homildon Hill Northumberland, England":"Battle, Berkshire, England","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stewart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: originally an occupational name for an administrative official of an estate, from Middle English <i>stiward</i>, Old English <i>stigweard</i>, <i>stīweard</i>, a compound of <i>stig</i> ‘house(hold)’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guardian’. In the Anglo-Saxon period this title was used of an officer controlling the domestic affairs of a household, especially of the royal household; after the Norman Conquest it was also used more widely as the native equivalent of <b>Seneschal</b>, for the steward of a manor or manager of an estate. In Scotland the term was also used of a magistrate originally appointed by the king to administer crown lands, forming a stewartry.","History: Stuart or Stewart is the surname of one of the great families of Scotland, the royal family of Scotland from the 14th century, and of England from 1603, when James VI of Scotland acceded to the English throne as James I. There were many minor branches of the family left in Britain after the flight of James II in 1688, but not every bearer of the surname can claim relationship with the royal house, even in Scotland. Every great house in medieval England and Scotland had its steward, and in many cases the office gave rise to a hereditary surname. The fall of the house of Stuart in Britain, conversely, led to the establishment of several highly placed branches bearing this surname in continental Europe, which are in most cases related to the old Scottish royal family."],"variants":[{"name":"Stuart","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire and Banffshire): variant of   Stewart  . This French form of the name, there being no W in the French language, was adopted by Mary, Queen of Scots, on her return to Scotland in 1561 and has since come to be more popular among royalists than the earlier spellings.","History: Stuart or Stewart is the surname of one of the great families of Scotland (see note at   Stewart  )."]},{"name":"Stewardson","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Westmorland): patronymic from Middle English <i>stiward</i> ‘steward’ (see   Stewart  ) + <i>-son</i> ‘son of the steward’."]},{"name":"Steward","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Stewart  ."]},{"name":"Steuart","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Stewart  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":16,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Stewart of Jedworth was born in 1366, in Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Alexander Stewart 5th Laird of Darnley, was 25 and his mother, Lady Marguerite Turnbull of Minto, was 34. He married Isabel Oliver about 1378, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 14 September 1402, in Battle, Berkshire, England, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1366–14 September 1402":"1366–14. september 1402","1366–1402":"1366–1402","1360–1410":"1360–1410","1381–1420":"1381–1420","1342–1404":"1342–1404","1332–1381":"1332–1381","before 1366":"enne 1366","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1404":"1404","1402":"1402","1366":"1366","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1378":"umbes 1378","about 1385":"umbes 1385","14 September 1402":"14. september 1402","Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Battle of Homildon Hill Northumberland, England":"Battle, Berkshire, England","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1366–14 September 1402":"1366–14. syyskuuta 1402","1366–1402":"1366–1402","1360–1410":"1360–1410","1381–1420":"1381–1420","1342–1404":"1342–1404","1332–1381":"1332–1381","before 1366":"ennen vuotta 1366","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1404":"1404","1402":"1402","1366":"1366","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","1420":"1420","1342":"1342","about 1378":"noin 1378","about 1385":"noin 1385","14 September 1402":"14. syyskuuta 1402","Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Darnley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Jedburgh, Roxburghshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Battle of Homildon Hill Northumberland, England":"Battle, Berkshire, England","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"1366–14 September 1402":"1366–14 septembre 1402","1366–1402":"1366–1